        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-objects-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Nodes And Edges",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -760,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Nodes And Edges Carry Meaning",
        "body": "The graph surface is not just decoration. Node placement, edge direction, and spacing help the learner see structure, flow, and relationship before they even open a properties panel.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-zoom-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Zoom And Pan",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": -300,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Zoom And Pan Are Reading Tools",
        "body": "Zoom and pan are how you change reading distance. Use them deliberately to move between whole-graph structure and local detail instead of treating them like emergency controls.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-map-note",
      "type": "tutorial-concept",
      "label": "Minimap And Semantic Zoom",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 160,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Minimap And Semantic Zoom Keep You Oriented",
        "body": "The minimap helps you keep track of where you are inside a larger graph, while semantic zoom changes what kind of surface is useful at different distances. Together they reduce disorientation.",
        "tag": "Concept",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-concept",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-concept",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-concept.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-concept",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-example",
      "type": "tutorial-example",
      "label": "Examples",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 640,
        "y": -520
      },
      "width": 400,
      "height": 240,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Examples",
        "body": "Use the sample note below as a short checklist for reading the graph surface. This lesson is about forming habits: read the shape of the graph, then zoom for detail, then use the minimap and semantic zoom to keep your bearings.",
        "cta": "Inspect the sample",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-example",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-example",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-example.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-example",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-sample-note",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "Surface Reading Checklist",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 640,
        "y": -120
      },
      "width": 430,
      "height": 300,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        },
        "markdown": "## Graph surface checklist\n\nWhen a graph opens, ask:\n\n- What are the major node groups?\n- Which edges feel directional or structural?\n- Am I zoomed too far in to see the overall shape?\n- Would panning or the minimap help me re-center?\n- At this distance, am I looking for icon, summary, or detail surfaces?\n\nThe graph surface is part of the teaching model, not just a background."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-challenge",
      "type": "tutorial-challenge",
      "label": "Challenge",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 1140,
        "y": -120
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 220,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Challenge",
        "body": "1. Open a graph with enough nodes to require zoom or pan.\n2. Describe the major structure before opening any details.\n3. Change zoom level on purpose and explain what becomes easier to see.\n4. Use the minimap or re-centering behavior to recover your place.\n5. Explain what semantic zoom is adding beyond simple scaling.",
        "difficulty": "starter",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-challenge",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-challenge.node-class.node",
          "ref": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-challenge.node-class.node"
        },
        "_bridge": {
          "classKey": "tutorial-challenge",
          "classRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-challenge.node-class.node"
        },
        "definitionKey": "tutorial-challenge",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "tutorial-interface-graph-surface"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "graph-surface-checkpoint",
      "type": "tutorial-checkpoint",
      "label": "Checkpoint",
      "root": false,
      "position": {
        "x": 1580,
        "y": -120
      },
      "width": 360,
      "height": 220,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Checkpoint",
        "body": "You are done when you can say:\n- the graph surface communicates structure before I inspect details\n- zoom and pan are deliberate reading tools\n- the minimap helps me stay oriented in larger graphs\n- semantic zoom changes which surface is useful at different distances\n- graph space itself is part of how Twilite teaches meaning",
        "status": "verify",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "tutorial-checkpoint",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/tutorial/basic-primitives/tutorial-checkpoint.node-class.node",
